\[severity:It bothers me. A fix would be nice\]  
Visual Studio version: Visual Studio 17.14.0 Preview 1.0  
C# project type: Console Application using .NET Framework 4.8

Input code
----------

```  
using System;
namespace Console48
{
    class A
    {
        internal A(int x, int y)
        {
        }
    }
    class Program
    {
        static void Main()
        {
            Console.WriteLine("{0}{1}", new A(1, 2), new A(3, 4));
        }
    }
}

```

Steps
-----
1. Go menu bar -&gt; Tools -&gt; Options... -&gt; Text Editor -&gt; C# -&gt; Code Style -&gt; General
2. Set "Prefer implicit object creation when type is apparent" on "Yes".
3. Run " Introduce local for 'new A(1, 2)' " in text editor.

Actual result
-------------

```  
using System;
namespace Console48
{
    class A
    {
        internal A(int x, int y)
        {
        }
    }
    class Program
    {
        static void Main()
        {
            A arg0 = new(1, 2);
            Console.WriteLine("{0}{1}", arg0, new A(3, 4));
        }
    }
}

```

1 Error  
CS8370: Feature ‘target-typed object creation’ is not available in C# 7.3. Please use language version 9.0 or greater.

Expected result
---------------

```  
using System;
namespace Console48
{
    class A
    {
        internal A(int x, int y)
        {
        }
    }
    class Program
    {
        static void Main()
        {
            A arg0 = new A(1, 2);
            Console.WriteLine("{0}{1}", arg0, new A(3, 4));
        }
    }
}

```

Setting `csharp_style_implicit_object_creation_when_type_is_apparent = true` on .editorconfig file can resolve this issue, but I think that quick action should not make code uncompilable regardless of editorconfig.


